<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<methodology slug="gce-autoscaling">
  <metadata>
    <tier>pro</tier>
    <group>infra</group>
    <domain>infrastructure-engineer</domain>
    <summary>Configure GCE autoscalers for MIGs using CPU, load-balancing, custom Cloud Monitoring metrics, schedule-based, and predictive signals with scale-in controls to prevent flapping.</summary>
    <tags>
      <tag>gcp</tag>
      <tag>compute-engine</tag>
      <tag>autoscaling</tag>
      <tag>performance</tag>
    </tags>
    <category>compute</category>
    <difficulty>intermediate</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-27</created>
    <related>
      <ref slug="gce-managed-instance-groups"/>
      <ref slug="gce-instance-templates"/>
    </related>
  </metadata>

  <content>
    <title>GCE Autoscaling</title>

    <summary>The GCE autoscaler adjusts the size of a Managed Instance Group in response to one or more scaling signals: CPU utilization, load balancing capacity, custom Cloud Monitoring metrics, time-based schedules, or ML-based predictive forecasting. Multiple signals can be combined; the autoscaler scales to whichever signal demands the most capacity. Scale-in controls prevent rapid downscaling that would cause flapping during brief traffic dips.</summary>

    <why>
      <p>Manual capacity management is slow (operator response time) and either over-provisions (wasting money) or under-provisions (degrading service). An autoscaler responds within 60 seconds of a signal change and continuously right-sizes the fleet. The initialization period prevents premature scale-in decisions while new VMs are still warming up. Predictive autoscaling extends reactive scaling with an ML forecast trained on cyclical traffic patterns, pre-warming capacity before demand arrives rather than reacting after latency has already risen.</p>
      <p>Scale-in controls are a critical safety feature: without them, a 30-second traffic dip after peak load causes the autoscaler to remove instances, which then creates capacity shortfall when traffic returns, triggering another scale-out — a flapping loop that degrades SLOs.</p>
    </why>

    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Any MIG-backed service with variable traffic — CPU-based autoscaling is the correct default.</item>
        <item>HTTP(S) services behind a Google Cloud Load Balancer — load balancing utilization signal tracks requests-per-second more accurately than CPU for frontend services.</item>
        <item>Queue-draining workers — custom Cloud Monitoring metric (queue depth) drives scaling proportional to backlog size.</item>
        <item>Predictable daily or weekly traffic patterns (e.g., business-hours web apps) — schedule-based autoscaling pre-provisions capacity before demand arrives.</item>
        <item>Applications with initialization time longer than 2 minutes — predictive autoscaling prevents latency spikes at ramp-up by starting instances before traffic arrives.</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>

    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Stateful MIGs where instance replacement destroys per-instance data — autoscaling removes instances without draining persistent state; use manual scaling or stateful MIG policies instead.</item>
        <item>MIGs with min_replicas = 0 for production services — a scale-to-zero event during a traffic dip causes a cold-start latency spike when traffic returns; keep minimum >= 1 (or >= 3 for regional MIGs).</item>
        <item>Workloads with unpredictable, spiky traffic (e.g., viral events) where the 60-second reaction time is too slow — pre-scale via a schedule or use Cloud Run/GKE with faster scale-to-zero.</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>

    <rules>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>The autoscaler's initialization_period (cooldown_period in Terraform) MUST be set greater than the VM startup time plus application warmup time. For applications with initialization > 2 minutes, predictive autoscaling MUST be enabled with OPTIMIZE_AVAILABILITY mode.</statement>
        <rationale>If the cooldown period is shorter than VM startup, the autoscaler observes high CPU on starting VMs and interprets it as demand, triggering additional scale-out when the existing scale-out has not yet registered. This results in over-provisioning proportional to the ratio of startup time to cooldown period.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Every autoscaler MUST configure scale_in_control with a time_window_sec of at least 600 seconds (10 minutes) and a max_scaled_in_replicas fixed count or percentage that prevents more than 20% of instances from being removed in that window.</statement>
        <rationale>Without scale-in controls, a traffic dip lasting 60+ seconds triggers aggressive scale-in. When traffic returns, the reduced fleet is undersized and latency rises while the autoscaler re-scales out. The 10-minute window smooths short traffic dips and prevents the flapping pattern.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Production autoscalers MUST set min_replicas to at least 1 for single-zone MIGs and at least 3 for regional MIGs. max_replicas MUST be set with cost awareness: calculate the maximum expected load at 60% CPU utilization to derive max_replicas, then add a 20% safety margin.</statement>
        <rationale>min_replicas = 0 causes a cold-start gap on every scale-to-zero event. max_replicas without a ceiling risks runaway scaling from a metric misconfiguration or DDoS event; the ceiling limits financial blast radius.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </rules>

    <section name="signal-types">
      <p>GCE supports five autoscaling signal types. Multiple signals can be combined on one autoscaler; the autoscaler uses the maximum recommended size across all active signals.</p>

      <list>
        <item>CPU utilization — scale based on average CPU across all instances in the MIG; target 60% for web apps and APIs (leaves headroom for traffic spikes).</item>
        <item>Load balancing capacity — requests per second or backend capacity from Cloud Load Balancing; most accurate for HTTP(S) frontends.</item>
        <item>Cloud Monitoring metric — custom metric such as queue depth, active connections, or inference latency; use GAUGE type with a per-instance assignment value.</item>
        <item>Schedule-based — cron expression with a minimum replica floor for predictable traffic patterns (e.g., business hours).</item>
        <item>Predictive — ML model trained on historical CPU patterns; produces a forecast and pre-scales before demand arrives; requires at least 1-2 weeks of historical data and predictable cyclical patterns.</item>
      </list>

      <example type="good" title="Multi-signal autoscaler: CPU + LB + custom metric + scale-in control">
        <code lang="hcl"><![CDATA[
resource "google_compute_region_autoscaler" "multi_signal" {
  name   = "multi-signal-autoscaler"
  region = "us-central1"
  target = google_compute_region_instance_group_manager.app.id

  autoscaling_policy {
    min_replicas    = 3
    max_replicas    = 50
    cooldown_period = 60

    cpu_utilization {
      target            = 0.6
      predictive_method = "OPTIMIZE_AVAILABILITY"
    }

    load_balancing_utilization {
      target = 0.8
    }

    metric {
      name   = "custom.googleapis.com/queue_messages"
      type   = "GAUGE"
      target = 100
    }

    scale_in_control {
      max_scaled_in_replicas {
        percent = 20
      }
      time_window_sec = 900
    }
  }
}
]]></code>
      </example>

      <example type="good" title="Schedule-based autoscaler for business hours">
        <code lang="hcl"><![CDATA[
resource "google_compute_region_autoscaler" "scheduled" {
  name   = "scheduled-autoscaler"
  region = "us-central1"
  target = google_compute_region_instance_group_manager.app.id

  autoscaling_policy {
    min_replicas    = 2
    max_replicas    = 30
    cooldown_period = 60

    cpu_utilization {
      target = 0.6
    }

    scaling_schedules {
      name                  = "business-hours"
      min_required_replicas = 10
      schedule              = "0 9 * * MON-FRI"
      duration_sec          = 32400  # 9 hours
      time_zone             = "America/New_York"
    }

    scaling_schedules {
      name                  = "peak-traffic"
      min_required_replicas = 20
      schedule              = "0 12 * * *"
      duration_sec          = 7200   # 2 hours
      time_zone             = "America/New_York"
    }
  }
}
]]></code>
      </example>

      <example type="bad" title="No scale-in control, no cooldown, min_replicas=0">
        <code lang="hcl"><![CDATA[
# BAD: no scale-in control, no cooldown configuration, min=0
resource "google_compute_region_autoscaler" "bad" {
  name   = "bad-autoscaler"
  region = "us-central1"
  target = google_compute_region_instance_group_manager.app.id

  autoscaling_policy {
    min_replicas = 0   # scale-to-zero → cold start on every traffic dip
    max_replicas = 100 # uncapped → runaway scaling risk

    cpu_utilization {
      target = 0.9  # 90% target leaves no headroom for spikes
    }
    # no scale_in_control → aggressive scale-in causes flapping
    # no cooldown_period → defaults to 60s; may be too short for slow startups
  }
}
]]></code>
        <note>90% CPU target means the autoscaler scales out only after VMs are already saturated; latency spikes precede the scale-out. min=0 produces cold starts. Missing scale-in controls cause flapping.</note>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="gcloud-commands">
      <commands>
        <command name="set-cpu-autoscaling"><![CDATA[gcloud compute instance-groups managed set-autoscaling my-mig \
    --region=us-central1 \
    --min-num-replicas=3 \
    --max-num-replicas=20 \
    --target-cpu-utilization=0.6 \
    --cool-down-period=60]]></command>
        <command name="set-lb-autoscaling"><![CDATA[gcloud compute instance-groups managed set-autoscaling my-mig \
    --region=us-central1 \
    --min-num-replicas=3 \
    --max-num-replicas=20 \
    --target-load-balancing-utilization=0.8]]></command>
        <command name="set-custom-metric"><![CDATA[gcloud compute instance-groups managed set-autoscaling my-mig \
    --region=us-central1 \
    --min-num-replicas=2 \
    --max-num-replicas=10 \
    --update-stackdriver-metric=custom.googleapis.com/queue_depth \
    --stackdriver-metric-single-instance-assignment=10]]></command>
        <command name="create-schedule"><![CDATA[gcloud compute instance-groups managed update-autoscaling my-mig \
    --region=us-central1 \
    --set-schedule=business-hours \
    --schedule-cron="0 9 * * MON-FRI" \
    --schedule-min-required-replicas=10 \
    --schedule-duration-sec=32400 \
    --schedule-time-zone="America/New_York"]]></command>
        <command name="enable-predictive"><![CDATA[gcloud compute instance-groups managed update-autoscaling my-mig \
    --region=us-central1 \
    --cpu-utilization-predictive-method=OPTIMIZE_AVAILABILITY]]></command>
        <command name="set-scale-in-control"><![CDATA[gcloud compute instance-groups managed update-autoscaling my-mig \
    --region=us-central1 \
    --scale-in-control-max-scaled-in-replicas=10 \
    --scale-in-control-time-window-sec=1200]]></command>
        <command name="stop-autoscaling"><![CDATA[gcloud compute instance-groups managed stop-autoscaling my-mig \
    --region=us-central1]]></command>
      </commands>
    </section>

    <section name="checklist">
      <checklist>
        <check>Autoscaling enabled on MIG with min_replicas >= 1 (never 0 for production).</check>
        <check>max_replicas set with cost ceiling awareness.</check>
        <check>cooldown_period (initialization period) greater than VM startup + app warmup time.</check>
        <check>CPU target utilization set to 60-80% (not 90%+) to leave headroom.</check>
        <check>scale_in_control configured with time_window_sec >= 600 and max 20% reduction per window.</check>
        <check>Multiple signals configured for complex workloads (CPU + custom metric).</check>
        <check>Predictive autoscaling enabled for apps with initialization > 2 minutes and predictable patterns.</check>
        <check>Schedule-based scaling configured for workloads with known traffic patterns.</check>
        <check>Custom Cloud Monitoring metric configured if queue depth or latency is the primary signal.</check>
        <check>Autoscaler decisions reviewed in Cloud Monitoring after first week of operation.</check>
      </checklist>
    </section>

    <section name="llm-prompts">
      <prompt purpose="configure-autoscaling"><![CDATA[
Configure autoscaling for a Managed Instance Group:

MIG details:
- Name: {mig_name}
- Region/Zone: {location}
- Current size: {size}

Scaling requirements:
- Minimum instances: {min}
- Maximum instances: {max}
- Target CPU utilization: {cpu_target}% (e.g., 60%)
- Cooldown period: {seconds}s

Additional signals (optional):
- Load balancer utilization target: {lb_target}
- Custom metric: {metric_name} with target {target_value}

Provide:
1. gcloud CLI command
2. Terraform google_compute_region_autoscaler resource
3. Scale-in control recommendations
4. Predictive autoscaling recommendation
5. Cost implications of configuration
]]></prompt>

      <prompt purpose="predictive-autoscaling"><![CDATA[
Enable predictive autoscaling for a workload:

Workload characteristics:
- Traffic pattern: {predictable daily, weekly cycles, unpredictable}
- Initialization time: {seconds} seconds
- Historical data available: {weeks} weeks

Current autoscaling:
- MIG: {mig_name}
- Current scaling signal: CPU at {target}%

Provide:
1. Recommendation: OPTIMIZE_AVAILABILITY vs FORECAST_ONLY
2. gcloud command to enable predictive autoscaling
3. Terraform configuration
4. Prerequisites checklist
5. How to monitor prediction accuracy
]]></prompt>

      <prompt purpose="troubleshoot-autoscaling"><![CDATA[
Troubleshoot autoscaling issues:

Symptoms:
- {symptom: e.g., "Autoscaler not scaling up during traffic spikes"}
- {symptom: e.g., "Scaling too aggressively, causing flapping"}
- {symptom: e.g., "VMs added but not receiving traffic"}

Current configuration:
- MIG: {mig_name}
- Autoscaling signal: {signal}
- Min/Max: {min}/{max}
- Cooldown: {cooldown}s
- Initialization period: {init_period}s

Provide:
1. Diagnostic gcloud commands
2. Key metrics to check in Cloud Monitoring
3. Common issues and solutions
4. Configuration adjustments to try
5. Scale-in control recommendations
]]></prompt>
    </section>

    <antipattern>
      <description>Setting the autoscaler cooldown period shorter than the VM startup time.</description>
      <reason>Starting VMs consume high CPU during initialization. A short cooldown causes the autoscaler to observe high CPU across the fleet and issue additional scale-out before the in-progress scale-out has had time to reduce the average CPU. This produces over-provisioning proportional to (startup_time / cooldown_period).</reason>
    </antipattern>

    <antipattern>
      <description>Using only CPU utilization as the autoscaling signal for an HTTP(S) frontend behind a load balancer.</description>
      <reason>CPU does not accurately reflect request rate for I/O-bound or network-bound services. A service can be CPU-idle while being request-saturated. Use load_balancing_utilization or a custom RPS metric as the primary signal for HTTP frontends.</reason>
    </antipattern>

    <antipattern>
      <description>Setting target CPU utilization above 80% for production autoscaling.</description>
      <reason>At 80-90% utilization there is no headroom for traffic spikes. By the time the autoscaler decides to scale out (after observing sustained high CPU), latency has already spiked. Target 60% to preserve 40% spike headroom; this is the documented GCP recommendation.</reason>
    </antipattern>

